cyclone.name: ETA
cyclone.current_location: about 45 miles NNW of Key West, Florida
cyclone.trajectory: Expected to drift west-southwest today, stall over the southeastern Gulf of Mexico Tuesday, then turn slowly north on Wednesday–Friday toward the Florida Big Bend/NE Gulf Coast.
cyclone.expected_landfall_location: Florida Big Bend coast (near Cedar Key)

weather_observation.watch_coast: Cuban provinces of La Habana, Artemisa, Mayabeque, Pinar del Rio and Isle of Youth (Tropical Storm Watch)
weather_observation.warning_coast: Northwestern Bahamas; Florida coast from Brevard/Volusia County line south-westward across the Keys to Anna Maria Island; Lake Okeechobee (Tropical Storm Warning)
weather_observation.impacted_coast: South and central Florida peninsula, Keys, southeastern Gulf of Mexico, then north Florida Gulf Coast and Georgia/South Carolina coasts late week
weather_observation.wind: Late Thursday into Friday, sustained winds 20–35 kt with occasional tropical-storm-force gusts possible as Eta’s remnants move inland to the west.
weather_observation.storm_surge: Minor tidal departures (<2 ft) possible along the St. Johns River and adjacent Atlantic beaches; significant surge not expected.
weather_observation.rainfall: 1–3 inches of rain possible Friday–Saturday with locally higher bands, producing ponding on dock surfaces.
weather_observation.other_hazards: Low tornado risk in outer rainbands late week; rough seas and hazardous swell for inbound/outbound vessels beginning Thursday.
